Question 2

Having observed a negative correlation between Cholesterol and Viral Load in Question 1, now we must quantify that relationship in more detail using a linear regression, lm() function.

chol_v_vload_model <- lm(chol ~ vload, data=mls3302_u1_assg4_dat)
summary(chol_v_vload_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = chol ~ vload, data = mls3302_u1_assg4_dat)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.2008 -0.8067  0.0624  0.6430  4.9792 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 157.222416   1.517201  103.63   <2e-16 ***
## vload        -0.113963   0.003069  -37.13   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.708 on 38 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9732, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9725 
## F-statistic:  1379 on 1 and 38 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The important results of the regression analysis:

  • t-Test if vload is a significant predictor of chol: p < 2.0x10-16
  • F-Test if the model we specified is a significant predictor of chol: p < 2.0x10-16
  • Regression Coefficients: Beta (slope) = -0.11396, Intercept = 157.22242
  • Adjusted R-squared: 0.972

t-Test: p < 2.0x10-16: This t-Test is testing if the independent x variable (vload) is a significant predictor of the dependent y (chol) variable. The null is is that it is not a predictor and the alternative is that it is associated or a predictor of the y variable.

F-Test: p < 2.0x10-16: The F-Test is testing if the model is a significant predictor of the dependent variable, model being all the independent variables we are interested in as predictors. For this class, we will be performing univariate analysis, so the t-Test and F-Test should be approximately equal.

Regression Coefficients: Are the values of the slope (Beta) and intercept obtained from the regression analysis and used to quantify the relationship between x and y. As well as produce a regression equation. For the homework, the beta coefficient tells us that for every unit increase in vload, there is an associated decrease of -0.11396 mg/dL in chol. And the regression equation would be:

chol=0.11396(vload)+157.22242chol=0.11396(vload)+157.22242

Adjusted R-squared: 0.972: The R2 gives a measure of how spread-out the points are from the regression line. If they lie directly on the line, R^2=1 (100%). The farther from the line the points are, the smaller the R2. We also can interpret the R2 in context of the variation in y explained by x. For example: The vload explains about 97% of the variation in cholesterol levels seen in this study.

Conclusion: The results of the regression analysis show that viral load is significantly associated with cholesterol levels (p < 2.0x1016). The viral load seems to explain about 97% of the variation in cholesterol levels, so overall our model is a good fit. The regression coefficients tell us that for every one increase in HIV viral load (copies/mL) there is an associated decrease of 0.11396 mg/dL in cholesterol levels.

It is always good to show a plot of the points with the fitted regression line.

chol_v_vload_regp <- ggplot(data=mls3302_u1_assg4_dat, aes(x=vload, y=chol)) + geom_point(size=3, shape=18) + theme_classic() + labs(title="Cholesterol vs. Viral Load", y="Cholesterol (mg/dL)", x="Viral Load (RNA copies/mL) ") + geom_abline(intercept=157.22242, slop=-0.11396, colour='purple') 
chol_v_vload_regp

Question 3

Regression Equation:

Cholesterol=0.11396(ViralLoad)+157.22242Cholesterol=0.11396(ViralLoad)+157.22242

If a patient had a Viral Load = 57 RNA copies/mL then:

-0.11396*57 + 157.22242
## [1] 150.7267

We would predict their cholesterol level to be 150.7 mg/dL

Bonus

Residual Plot: The residual plot takes the residuals (actual dependent variable values - predicted dependent variable values) on the y-axis and plots them for every value of the dependent variable placed on the x-axis.

model_resid <- resid(chol_v_vload_model)
resid_plot <- ggplot(data=mls3302_u1_assg4_dat, aes(x=chol, y=model_resid)) + geom_point(size=3, shape=18) + theme_classic() + geom_abline(intercept=0, slope=0, colour='red') + labs(title='Residuals vs. Cholesterol', y='Residuals', x='Cholesterol')
resid_plot

Conclusion: The residuals appear to be randomly spread around the zero line. That is, there appears to be no pattern to their distribution around the zero line. This supports our assumption of homescedasticity of the residuals.
